McCain and Russian Dossier

Senator John McCain played a significant role in the dissemination of the so-called "Trump-Russia dossier," a collection of memos compiled by former British spy Christopher Steele that contained allegations about then-President-elect Donald Trump's potential ties to Russia. McCain first learned about the dossier during the Halifax International Security Forum in November 2016, where he was approached by a retired British diplomat, Sir Andrew Wood, who introduced him to Steele's findings.

McCain, who had a long-standing reputation as a staunch critic of Russian President Vladimir Putin, felt that even unverified allegations of Russian influence over Trump warranted further investigation. After learning about the dossier, McCain directed David Kramer, a former State Department official and Russia expert who was familiar with Steele's work, to travel to London to meet Steele directly. Kramer obtained a copy of the dossier and returned to the United States, where he shared it with McCain and his staff.

McCain described the information in the dossier as "disturbing" but unverified, and he decided to pass it on to then-FBI Director James Comey for further investigation. He met with Comey on December 9, 2016, and delivered the dossier, stating that it was his duty to ensure that any potential national security threats were investigated thoroughly.

In his 2018 memoir, "The Restless Wave," McCain defended his actions, writing that he had an obligation to bring the information to the attention of appropriate officials. He stated, "I discharged that obligation, and I would do it again. Anyone who doesn't like it can go to hell".

McCain was not the originator of the dossier, nor did he commission its creation. The dossier was originally compiled by Steele, who was working under contract with Fusion GPS, a research firm that had been hired by the Democratic National Committee and the law firm representing Hillary Clinton's campaign to conduct opposition research on Trump.

McCain was also aware of the sensitivity of the information and urged Kramer to ensure that it was handled responsibly. Kramer, in a deposition, revealed that he shared the dossier with several news organizations, including BuzzFeed News, the Washington Post, and the Wall Street Journal, but emphasized the need for verification and cautioned against premature publication.

Despite McCain's efforts to keep the information confidential and within official channels, the dossier was eventually published by BuzzFeed News on January 10, 2017, sparking widespread controversy and media attention.

McCain's role in the dossier affair was later criticized by President Trump, who accused McCain of acting with "evil purposes" and of being involved in a politically motivated effort to undermine his presidency. However, McCain's defenders, including his daughter Meghan McCain and fellow Republican Senator Lindsey Graham, argued that McCain acted out of a sense of duty and national security concern, and that his actions were appropriate given the potential implications of the allegations.

McCain maintained that he did not share the dossier with the press and that his only action was to pass it to the FBI for investigation. He also denied any involvement in the eventual leak of the dossier to the public, stating that he had kept the information in his office safe until he could hand it over to Comey.
